div.div: F1 is a piece of worked antler. Full recording: DS and >4mm flot. There are three worked bone fragments in this unit. This is a medium size unit, small for a midden. Excavators noted that this unit is sandwiched vertically between two fire spots. They also noted that there were a lot of animal bones and phytoliths in this unit. The bones are mostly sheep-size (85%), and the rest are cow-size, and a few hare-size fragments. Surface condition varies, but most bones are moderately weathered (3-4). The unit looks fairly fresh, it did not lie on the surface for a long time. There are also several relatively complete fragile elements indicating very swift deposition, no dog access, trampling, no processing, ergo food wastage (e.g. nearly complete os coxae and horn cores, very fresh looking, fragile, plausibly complete in the ground). About half of the sheep-size long bone scrap are spiral in shape, broken when the bone is fresh. Fragment size: This unit seems bimodal in size. Most of the bones are 3-5 cm, but about 10% are considerably larger, about 10 cm. Sheep-size long bone scrap (80% of long bone scrap) ranges between 12-2 cm, and the mode is about 4 cm. Cow-size long bone scraps range between 18-3 cm. The mode is about 8 cm. Sheep-size ribs are 12-1, with a mode of 4 cm. ADD Gnawing infoâ€¦ Fair amount of digestion in the smaller pieces, 30-40% of the whole unit. Modern breaks only make up 25% of the whole unit. Burning is 1%, these are 003 carbonized long bone scrap. There is a large number of diagnostics in this unit, 40% of the whole unit. This is due to large identifiable fragments, as well as the high number of cranial elements (including teeth). Diagnostics belong to human, canid, cattle, sheep/goat, and medium equid. Human diagnostic is a long bone fragment, possibly fibula. Canid diagnostics are a metapodial fragment (fox) and an ulna fragment (medium dog size). Medium size equid diagnostic is a tibia cylinder with red coloring inside the bone. The color looks like cinnabar (checked with conservation Duygu). There is no coloring on the external surface of the bone. It does not look like an intentional coloring, maybe cinnabar was in the deposit. There is also a distal radius that may be from a medium size equid. Sheep/goat diagnostics are cranial, all the long bones, feet, sacrum and pelvis. Even though all sheep/goat body parts are present, the body part distribution is uneven. There is a higher number of cranial and pelvis diagnostics compared to long bone diagnostics, but this is probably due to processing of long bones. Long bone diagnostics are biased towards the hindlimb. From forelimb, there are two humeri fragments, two radius fragments, 4-5 metacarpal fragments. From hindlimb, there are 7 femoral heads, only one femur cylinder, and 6 tibia fragments carrying large portions of the shaft, belonging to 5-6 tibia in total. There are 4-5 metatarsal fragments as well. (Tibias stand out from the other long bones as they are big pieces, and one is even complete.) These may be for bone working, considering the fact that there is an additional worked distal tibia, and one worked (possibly tibia) long bone shaft fragment in the unit. Sheep/goat: a range of ages are present, including infants. It is possible to calculate sheep/goat MNIs even though body part representation is uneven, and whole animals might not have been present in this unit. There are six sheep/goat ilium articulations (at acetabulum) (MNI:4). There are six sheep/goat coronoid processes (MNI:3). There are 6 left sheep/goat lower third molars (MNI: 6). Cattle diagnostics are less frequent, but these are large fragments. Diagnostics are a proximal ulna articulation, cranial, horn cores, acetabulum fragment, mandible, teeth, toes. Body part representation: All body parts are present in sheep/goat. Not all body parts are present in cattle, and the representation does not focus on any body part, such as meaty vs. non-meaty. Overall, this unit is bimodal: Most of it looks like standard midden, dominated by domestic consumption indicated by the fair amount of sheep/goat long bone and rib scrap, and some vertebrae. However it is not a typical domestic-consumption unit because there are also indications of other activities. The tibiae and the worked bones suggest that this may have been a tool making area. Some of the bones show no evidence of trampling or processing, these are pieces such as fragile, nearly complete and fresh os coxae. Apart from these very fresh looking bones, most of the bones in this unit were deposited quickly, but dogs clearly had access to it. <4mm FLOT, sample 2, flot number 8224. Diagnostics are pulled out, everything else is treated as flot frags. Medium size flotation sample. Consistent with the more daily-looking portion of the dry sieve: looks like the processed caprine part of it, but on the whole lacks the big, lightly weathered pieces. 98% sheep-size remains, the rest are cattle size, except one hare-size, and a micromammal fragment. There are no burnt bones except 2-3 carbonized fragments. Surface condition is moderate wear, majority is surface condition 4, some are 3. As in the dry-sieved, there are a lot of digested bones (40%). Fragment size for the whole flotation sample ranges between 1-13 cm; modal length is 1-2 cm. The flotation sample does not seem as bimodal as the dry sieve in terms of fragment length--except for ca. 3 large (10-13 cm) pieces, all fragments are 1-4 cm, and the majority of the fragments are 1-2 cm long. Diagnostics make up 5-10% of the flotation sample. Diagnostics include sheep/goat, small carnivore, fish, and microfauna. The sheep/goat diagnostics include all parts of the body. Thereâ€™s one large mandible fragment that echoes the multiple large mandible pieces in the dry sieve. Body part distribution is similar to the dry sieve in that thereâ€™s lots of cranial, and this is probably due to processing of long bones. There is a bone point in this flotation sample.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
